answers.body_markdown:
I anticipate having many different screens once all functionality will be implemented ( and hope that the user 
still find it&#39;s simple to use. UX on ONE . Always. It seems.  
Hence I will use many small steps ( screens ), like wizards style, instead of one &#39;complicated&#39; big screen.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
So a single mainform and a tabcontrol with &#39;some&#39; tabs,  does not seem to be a good choice :-). Imagine, you have 50tabs with many components and one day you load the project and the IDE doesn&#39;t want to render the form anymore with some exotic error message...-- yes, I&#39;ve seen it...anyone else ? :-).
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
But how then to model all those screens ? My first attempt , for me the most logical , was using frames. Only 1 main form and it loads
the frames in the mainform available client area ( while having some overal static controls on the mainform ). Frames are lightweight
and you can size and,if ever required, you can position them easily when align is not &#39;client&#39;. 
&lt;br /&gt;
I use a self managed stack of frames to add/remove ( push/pop ) a frame when user clicks on the relevant component or returns back.
So I create it once, then make the frame visible or not , reusing the instance for performance. Maybe later I should verify/manage memory consumption.. . 
But it results in a consistent look and feel. Me happy.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Unfortunately...you need to come in style.
&lt;br /&gt;
If styling ( at design time ) is important -- or might be, who knows at this point  -- frames lack severe shortcomings. In brief, they are not styled at design time...
I&#39;m not sure at this point, if it&#39;s important for me, but it gives me a very uncomfortable feeling..We&#39;ve come 30years in RAD visual development with Borland, sorry, Embarcadero,
products..so , really ?
&lt;br /&gt;
I tried many of the suggested workarounds, but I did not succeed in getting them styled like forms ( Yes, if you copy existing styles, rename them and use your own stylenames
on the frame components, then they somehow style a bit, but not completely. So in my opinion, that&#39;s not worth at all the ( dirty ) effort.
But yes, it&#39;s &#39;strange&#39; that apparently some styling can be done technically, so it feels frustrating that there is no &#39;default&#39; logic in place that renders frames like forms using e.g. the  stylebook of (single) main form..How hard to implement could that be... ?
&lt;br /&gt;
Anyway..
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Another (indirect) issue, happens when you need to use a component that apparently uses an underlying &#39;native&#39; platform control, e.g. twebbrowser. It&#39;s known for it&#39;s &#39;on top&#39; behaviour and hides every other component it overlaps ( at least at this date -- it seems anticipated to be resolved together with other z-order fixes... ). As I found twebbrowser, the only reliable, flexible videoplayer (!) for local and remote video ( by the way, that also took me some time to find out the hard way...) , so using it, is definitly a must have for me. 
And this issue is then really a showstopper ( very unprofessional in an app... ).
&lt;br /&gt;
I did find a &#39;workaround&#39; for the time when the browser could get scrolled of the screen ( and e.g. hiding my main toolbar ), that was to make it unvisible and show a text instead that it would return visible when coming again full in the view...I know, ugly, but what can you do.. ?
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; 
Back to the drawing board....
&lt;br /&gt;
The result of the above is that there is no other option for me then to use forms anyway...and try to fix their shortcomings ( the most important : they always show fullscreen on mobile..).
Sofar, I have done the following, I use a main form and I also use forms for every screen ( don&#39;t forget to remove it from your project source where it&#39;s auto-created... ).
I still use the stack to manage the user screen flow.
The &#39;trick&#39; not to make them full screen is to set them with borderstyle &#39;none&#39; and formstyle &#39;popup&#39;. So, visually, they behave like the frames now : they are loaded into the available client area of the mainform ( it&#39;s a bit tricky to position them correctly though...) . And I don&#39;t notice any performance issue from using the &#39;heavy&#39; form component. 
Also...Bingo, as a very welcomed side effect this also fixes the twebbrowser issue !!! The webbrowser on these forms no longers hides the mainform when moved around !!! Me happy.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Remark : Although it feels better to have the stylebook on a separate datamodule, I found it a little bit more stable when it&#39;s on the mainform. So, yes, all other forms &#39;use&#39;
the mainform to link the stylebook at the interface level. I don&#39;t think it&#39;s too bad, as all my &#39;child&#39; forms, are indeed controlled by the mainform and logically dependant. They are not standalone reusable forms...Whenever the mainform or another form, needs access to another form logic ( e.g. to load it ), it&#39;s added in the implementation &#39;use&#39; section.
( obviously, the only option for the mainform to have these as otherwise we have circular unit referencing ). 
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
So far so good but.....( oh yeah... ).
&lt;br /&gt;
Popup forms are handled in a special way by TScreen. They are closed automatically in case of some specific events ( like going to other app and return ). Probably many more things can cause this too. On mobile you can&#39;t click outside of the current app screen like on windows but still I think I need to &#39;handle&#39; it or suddenly my user sees the startup screen again ( the only non popup form ). Luckily this time, forms are indeed &#39;heavy&#39; :-) and I add in the onclosequery that they should never close ( CanClose = false, so no more automatic popup closing ) ! And my app uses the hide/show procedures to handle having them visible or not. ( there a subtile differences between hide and close -- without free-- but for me it works perfect ). The forms are all owned by the main form and freed together. It seems no problem that they are not really closed before. But anyway you could handle that with your own logic in &#39;onclosequery&#39; and allow them only to close at the end.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
So far so good but.....There is a remark about popup forms in the documentation, that makes me worry a bit, &quot;popup forms can never be active&quot;. Although I&#39;ve not encountered anything specific about it sofar except that indeed the &#39;onactivate&#39; event never fires ( but my popupforms can get the focus, they can be edited etc...), I&#39;m afraid that it will haunt me at some unexpected point. So in my final design, I reversed the both form usages : I have normal forms for each app screen and I use 1 &#39;popup&#39; toolbar form that I position at screen navigation. So now my forms are &#39;normal&#39;, and now only one special popup form is in use, which limits the risk. And, yes, also a webbrowser on these normal forms will not overlap my floating popup toolbar when scrolled off screen ! Me happy.


I hope I&#39;ve had the last surprise in all of this but for sure, I will keep you posted. As forms are indeed heavy, I trust that I will be able to fix any further issue elegantly :-).
Me happy. Afterall. 
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
As soon as a I have final stable code, I will post some snippets.

&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I hope this helps some people while making their own design choices.
&lt;br /&gt;

